However, what makes the other two classes distinct is sort of muddy. also, some of the results seem counter-intuitive. E.g., class 4 is high on correctness and but also on carelessness, which seems antithetical.

Part B: Once again, use the institutional library (e.g. NCSU Library), Google Scholar or search engine to locate a research article, presentation, or resource that applies unsupervised machine learning to an educational context aligned with your research interests. More specifically, locate a machine learning study that involve using Latent Profile Analysis or a similar method. You may find the published papers that have used LPA helpful in this respect; those can be browsed here.

  1. Provide an APA citation for your selected study.

    • Liu, F., Yang, D., Liu, Y. et al. Use of latent profile analysis and k-means clustering to identify student anxiety profiles. BMC Psychiatry 22, 12 (2022). https://doi.org/10.1186/s12888-021-03648-7

  2. What research questions were the authors of this study trying to address and why did they consider these questions important?

    • The study was largely exploratory, and the authors did not explictly state any research questions. however, they are broadly insterestied in understanding student anxiety for the purpose of promoting psychological well-being and creating targeted interventions.

  3. What were the results of these analyses?

    • they used LPA to create 3 different anxiety profiles (low, mild, and high risk). The low risk profile tended to be lower on all dimensions, while the mild and high risk differed the most on body anxiety, phobia ansiety, and impulsive tendencies.

data <- data %>% 
    select(q1,q2,q3,q4,q5,q6,q7,q8,q9,q10)


scale_data <- function(x) {
    x = x - mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)
    x = x / sd(x, na.rm = TRUE)
    x
}

data <- data %>%
    mutate_all(funs(scaled = scale_data)) %>% # using our function to scale all of the variables
    select(contains("_scaled")) # selecting only the scaled version

our_solution <- data %>%
    estimate_profiles(3)

plot_profiles(our_solution, add_line = TRUE)

There seems to be a clear distinction with each class across all questions. Class 3 > Class 1 > Class 2. However, the biggest distinction appears on Q8. ### Knit & Submit

  1. Change the name of the author: in the YAML header at the very top of this document to your name. As noted in Reproducible Research in R, The YAML header controls the style and feel for knitted document but doesn’t actually display in the final output.

  2. Click the yarn icon above to “knit” your data product to a HTML file that will be saved in your R Project folder.

  3. Commit your changes in GitHub Desktop and push them to your online GitHub repository.

  4. Publish your HTML page the web using one of the following publishing methods:

    • Publish on RPubs by clicking the “Publish” button located in the Viewer Pane when you knit your document. Note, you will need to quickly create a RPubs account.

    • Publishing on GitHub using either GitHub Pages or the HTML previewer.
